or importance for treating them. Instead, the contributors argue that labeling mental suffering as "illness" or "disorder" is often highly problematic; that the countries of South and Southeast Asia have abundant, though non- psychiatric, resources for dealing with it; that its causes are often social and biographical; and that many non-pharmacological therapies are effective for dealing with it. In short, they advocate a thoroughgoing mental health pluralism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCultural pluralism. 0aMental healthvCross-cultural studies. 0aMental healthzSouth Asia. 0aMental healthzSoutheast Asia. 0aMental illnessvCross-cultural studies. 0aMental illnesszSouth Asia. 0aMental illnesszSoutheast Asia. 0aPsychiatry. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary Society. 4aHealth and Medicine. 7aMEDICAL / Alternative & Complementary Medicine.2bisacsh  aasian medicine, mental health, psychiatry, medical pluralism, medical anthropology.1 aBihari Mukharji, Projit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Anindya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEcks, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalliburton, Murphy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHornbacher, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Claudia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNaraindas, Harish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuack, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRao, Mohan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSax, Will